---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import ProvingGround from '../../components/ProvingGround.tsx';
---

<Base
  title="The Proving Ground — pathtoAGI"
  description="Play the same sealed-world probes the frontier models face. Two revealed practice levels, then one live sealed world where your attempt becomes real human-baseline data for the record."
  ogImage="/media/proving-ground-hero.webp"
>
  <section class="max-w-3xl">
    <p class="eyebrow">The Proving Ground · play the test</p>
    <h1 class="display mt-4 text-4xl sm:text-5xl">You versus the sealed world</h1>
    <p class="lede mt-6">
      The Observatory tests whether a mind can find the rule of a world that
      never existed before — without being told what kind of rule to look for.
      Frontier models have taken these exact probes. Now you can too. Two
      levels are revealed, for practice. The third is live and sealed: no one
      grading you knows the answer, and your attempt becomes real human-baseline
      data the verdict actually requires.
    </p>
  </section>

  <figure class="mt-8 overflow-hidden border hairline" style="border-radius: 10px; background: var(--color-surface);">
    <img
      src="/media/proving-ground-hero.webp"
      alt="A human hand and a robotic hand reaching toward the same glowing puzzle grid on an antique brass observatory table, star charts behind."
      class="block aspect-[16/9] w-full object-cover"
      loading="eager"
      decoding="async"
    />
    <figcaption class="px-4 py-3 text-xs" style="color: var(--color-faint);">
      Same puzzle, two kinds of mind. The human baseline is not decoration — it
      is verdict gate OG-9, the calibration without which a machine score means
      nothing.
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <section class="mt-10">
    <ProvingGround client:visible />
  </section>

  <section class="mt-14 max-w-3xl">
    <h2 class="serif text-2xl">Why a game, honestly</h2>
    <p class="prose mt-4">
      This is not gamification for engagement. The verdict-change protocol
      requires a <strong>human baseline</strong> — competent people attempting
      the identical sealed probe — before any machine result can move the
      operating verdict. Collecting that baseline at scale, from strangers, on
      the exact worlds the models faced, is the honest use of a playable
      surface. Every Level-3 submission is stored, and when the seal opens it is
      graded by the same mechanical grader as the machine attempts, and the
      comparison is published — flattering or not. You are not the product here;
      you are a co-author of the baseline.
    </p>
    <p class="mono mt-4 text-xs" style="color: var(--color-faint);">
      Levels 1–2 grade in your browser against the already-revealed laws
      (<a href="/experiments/fcs-synth-world-006/REVEAL.md" class="hover:underline" style="color: var(--color-accent);">world-006</a>,
      <a href="/experiments/fcs-synth-world-005/REVEAL.md" class="hover:underline" style="color: var(--color-accent);">world-005</a>).
      Level 3 is <a href="/runs/" class="hover:underline" style="color: var(--color-accent);">world-003</a>, still sealed.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Netlify form registration (hidden): captures Level-3 human-baseline attempts -->
  <form name="human-baseline-world-003" netlify netlify-honeypot="bot-field" hidden>
    <input type="text" name="bot-field" />
    <textarea name="attempt"></textarea>
  </form>
</Base>
